For the `_.get` method an index must be used when defining a path that contains an Array. For example `_.get(object, 'a[0].b.c');`. Using an index may lead to unexpected results when for example the number / order of values in an Array are not constant. Therefore I'd like to suggest a "named index" for defining such a path. Currently, incorporating the `_.findIndex` can be used as a workaround but is far from elegant.

````javascript
// suggested path
_.get(obj, ['contact', ['key' : 'workPhone'], 'value'])
// or
_.get(obj, 'contact['key':'workPhone'].value')
````

````javascript
var obj = {
  'contact':
    [{
      'key': 'mobilePhone',
      'value': '555-555-551'
    },
    {
      'key': 'workPhone',
      'value': '555-555-552'
    }]
};

// current implementation
// var index = _.findIndex(obj.contact, ['key', 'workPhone']);
var workPhone = _.get(obj, 
                      [
                       'contact', 
                       // use index or an _.findIndex(...)
                       _.findIndex(obj.contact, ['key', 'workPhone']), 
                       // ...
                       'value'
                      ]
                     );
````

Problem: _.get returns undefined if you try to get value from key with depth more than first level.
How it works now:
```js
import { get } from 'lodash';

const object = {
    i18n: {
        menu: {
            main: 'b'
        }
    }
};

let i18n, menu, main;

i18n = get(object, [ 'i18n' ]); // { menu: { main: 'b' }} – correct
menu = get(object, [ 'i18n', 'menu' ]); // undefined
menu = get(object, 'i18n.menu'); // undefined
menu = get(object, [ 'i18n.menu' ]); // undefined
main = get(object, [ 'i18n', 'menu', 'main' ]); // undefined
main = get(object, 'i18n.menu.main'); // undefined
main = get(object, [ 'i18n.menu.main' ]); // undefined
```
How it should work:
```js
menu = get(object, [ 'i18n', 'menu' ]); // { main: 'b' }
menu = get(object, 'i18n.menu'); // { main: 'b' }
main = get(object, [ 'i18n', 'menu', 'main' ]); // 'b'
main = get(object, 'i18n.menu.main'); // 'b'
```
Version: 4.17.4

Hello,

As usual, first thanks for this great library.

I spent a lot of time reading lodash documentation, and that's why it is important to me that it is clear and easily understandable. The documentation of pick is making me spent more time trying to understand the functionality than actually using it. Many times I found myself on a repl making tests to see what is capable of and what not.
The first confusing part is the parameter naming. The function signature includes `paths` as part of the input arguments, but the description says properties.
The example being too simplistic does not help neither. At the end of the pick section you don't know if you can use object paths or if you can only use plain properties.
I made some experiments with different and unexpected results. For example, taking the example as base and making a small modification the result is as expected:

```js
var object = { 'a': 1, 'b': '2', 'c': { d: 99, e: 88 }};
 
_.pick(object, ['a', 'c.d']);
// => { 'a': 1, 'c': { d: 3 } }
```

Trying to go further and adding an array, the result is also satisfactory:

```js
object2 = { 'a': 1, 'b': '2', 'c': [{ d: 99, e: 88 }]};
_.pick(object2, ['a', 'c.0.d']);
// => { 'a': 1, 'c': [{ d: 3 }] }
```

However none of those functionalities is documented, and it is hard to figure them out. Specially the array paths. One can think that the correct way of defining them may be `c[0].d` but it is not.
I think expanding the base example a bit further will help immensely.

Thanks in advance.

I'm attempting to use the FP version of `mergeWith` with a customizer that overwrites a particular target field (an array value).  It appears to work fine with the non-FP version of `mergeWith`, but not the FP version.

```
const assert = require('assert');

const cloneDeep = require('lodash/cloneDeep');
const nonFpMergeWith = require('lodash/mergeWith');
const mergeWith = require('lodash/fp/mergeWith');

const mutableOrigData = {
  foo: 123,
  bar: {
    baz: 'quux'
  },
  properties: [{ name: 'origName', value: 'origValue' }]
};
const origData = cloneDeep(mutableOrigData);


const updates = {
  foo: 456,
  bar: { newField: 'new' },
  properties: [{ name: 'n1', value: 'v1' }]
};

const expected = {
  foo: 456,
  bar: {
    baz: 'quux',
    newField: 'new'
  },
  properties: [{ name: 'n1', value: 'v1' }]
}


function nonFpCustomizer(objValue, srcValue, key) {
  if (key === 'properties') {
    return srcValue;
  }
}

function customizer(srcValue, objValue, key) {
  if (key === 'properties') {
    return srcValue;
  }
}


nonFpMergeWith(mutableOrigData, updates, nonFpCustomizer);
// This does NOT throw (works as expected)
assert.deepEqual(expected, mutableOrigData);
// This throws.  Although the `bar` and `properties` fields are handled correctly, `foo` isn't?
assert.deepEqual(expected, mergeWith(customizer, updates, origData));
```

What am I missing?

